No, you cannot ignore a div, but a simple workaround in your case would be to not use a background-color on the middle div at all, and then color the outer element&#39;s **border** instead of its background color:

- `.timelineElementMitte`: Change background to `background-color: none` (or just remove it).
- `.timelineElementAu&#223;en`: Remove `background-color`, add `border: 0 solid white`
- `.timelineElementAu&#223;en:hover`: Remove `padding`, add `border-width: 25px`



&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: null --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    body {
      background-color: white
    }

    .timelineElementInnen {
      z-index: 3;
      background-color: white;
      border-radius: 50px;
      height: 100px;
      width: 100px;
    }

    .timelineElementMitte {
      z-index: 2;
      border-radius: 50px;
      background-color: none; /* replaces background-color: gray; */
      transition: 1000ms;
      width: 100px;
      height: 100px;
      padding: 0px;
    }

    .timelineElementMitte:hover {
      padding: 25px;
      border-radius: 75px;
    }

    .timelineElementAu&#223;en {
      z-index: 1;
      border-radius: 50px;
      transition: 1000ms;
      width: 100px;
      height: 100px;
      padding: 0px;
      border: 0 solid white; /* replaces background-color: white; */
      margin: 50px;
    }

    .timelineElementAu&#223;en:hover {
      width: 150px;
      height: 150px;
      border-radius: 100px;
      border-width: 25px; /* replaces padding: 25px; */
      margin: 0px;
    }

